Not sure if this is related or not, but we found a large performance boost by slightly modifying ZipFile.extractFile() methods. We changed the code to do a conditional around readZipInfo() as follows:

`if (zipModel == null) {
  readZipInfo();
}`

Hope this helps the investigation.

@osterwiese Aes encryption works perfectly fine for me. Can you please post the code you used? Here is the code I tested with:

```
@Test
public void testAesEncryptedZipFile() throws IOException {
  ZipParameters zipParameters = new ZipParameters();
  zipParameters.setEncryptFiles(true);
  zipParameters.setEncryptionMethod(EncryptionMethod.AES);
  zipParameters.setAesKeyStrength(AesKeyStrength.KEY_STRENGTH_256);

  ZipFile zipFile = new ZipFile(BASE_DIR + "aes.zip", "password".toCharArray());
  zipFile.addFile(BASE_DIR + "TEST_FILE_9999.txt", zipParameters);

  File extractDir = new File(BASE_DIR + "extracted/");
  if (!extractDir.exists()) {
    extractDir.mkdirs();
  }

  zipFile = new ZipFile(BASE_DIR + "aes.zip", "password".toCharArray());
  zipFile.extractAll(extractDir.getPath());
}
```

Please note that windows zip tool has trouble extracting aes encrypted zip files. A brief explanation of this is described in the issue [here][1]. If you have used Windows zip tool to test it, please test it with some other tool. I tested the zip file generated with zip4j, with several other tools (including extracting with zip4j) and it worked fine each time.

[1]: https://github.com/srikanth-lingala/zip4j/issues/113#issuecomment-560584399
